Hi! I'm Alec, and I made the autograders for this course. Because we're handling user code, there are a lot of unexpected places where things could go wrong. This might lead to the message "Grader Failed" when submitting your assignments. If you see that, please do the following:
  • Make sure you're submitting the right files. I've seen .class files submitted before instead of .java files on accident, and the compiler really doesn't like those.
  • Submit a bug report by clicking the flag at the bottom of the assignment page, then clicking "Grader Problem". This allows me to see the grader output, your code, and what exactly went wrong.
  • NOTE - You no longer need to make a post on this board. Coursera now allows us to reply directly to bug reports.
    • Thanks for participating in the course, and I hope you enjoy it!

We want you to become very comfortable asking questions and responding to others' questions on the Discussion forum. It will be your main source of support for this course.So to get you started in the forum, introduce yourself to your classmates by posting the following information:
  • Your name
  • Where you live
  • What you hope to get out of this class/why you are taking this class
  • Anything else you want to share about yourself

Someone faced with the problem of incorrect construction of the route using the cache? The problem is that when using the A * algorithm, we can get the cached route, and use it, although it will be less than optimal. As can be seen from the figure, S1-F route has been cached, we are trying to build S2-F route. The algorithm A * go to the vertice of the P2 and get the cached route S2-P1-P2-P3-P4-P5-P7-P8-F. Although the shortest route will be S2-P1-P6-F. Someone was able to solve this problem?
